snippet.textDisplay: You found out why you should not use a pressure washer. For wood decks, it tears into the wood surface, so the wood looks like crap sooner. My advice - either peel off the plasti-dip and start over, or go to a home improvement store and buy a rough surface sponge. Use it to add splotches of a darker color of plasti-dip, like a camouflage to cover and hide all of the imperfections. WatchJRGo has a recent video about working on the existing old paint for a Saab, probably better than adding thousands of dollars of paint or wrap to a car worth less than that. Hagerty has a good written article about car paint prep for a new Miata- instead of clay I have found that spraying PB Blaster penetrating oil on the paint and rubbing it with a microfiber cloth, after washing, removes a lot of the  gritty air pollution fallout. For polish, rubbing compound; and for wax, the orange bottle of liquid Nu Finish from a Walmart, also for the outside of the windshield glass.

snippet.textDisplay: I've dipped a few vehicles, using the right equipment. It looks awesome for about 6 months, then it starts to fade and thin, after a year it looks really bad, and you can not touch it up. I used "dip" spray on wax, garaged my vehicles, and laid down 7-10 coats of dip. For 300'ish (once you own the gun) it's great, but for the amount of work to clean/mask/tape/spray you could be laying down real paint. But Dip is very user friendly, much easier then paint because it naturally blends into the previous coats. I stopped dipping and started vinyl wrapping, just my motorcycle, and i must say wrap is much, much better. it is cheap, easy, and durable. easy on bike parts, a car would be much harder. but 3 years, 15,000 miles, and mu bike looks as good as the day i wrapped it! just my experience. great vid guys!
